## My notes

### Chp. 3

What is the effect of a man’s work on his outlook of the world? The _**working personality**_. Intense professions like policing produce _**styles of life**_. The working personality is shaped by **danger** and **authority** and **a need to be efficient**. Causes the police officer to be a **suspicious person**, and it makes it hard for them to make friends.

Officers have to enforce laws they might not often believe in undermining morale. In fact, the character needed to enforce puritanical law is not the character needed to have the requisite toughness and attunement to danger to enforce such law. Leads to dissonance. **Police solidarity** where they can break the law together away from civilians who will think them hypocrites.

Danger also undermines the judicious use of authority. Police officers in the USA are more fearful because we have a more dangerous society.

Police officers develop a shorthand for identifying dangerous peoples and dealing with/identifying potential violence. _**Symbolic assailants**_ (people who use gesture, language, and attire police identify as preludes to violence). **Danger** is integral to their work. Identifying it and preventing it.

Short passage from James Baldwin → “The only way to police a ghetto is to be oppressive… their very presence is an insult… even if they spend their entire day feeding gumdrops to children. They represent the force of the white world… it is hard to blame the policeman, blank, good-natured, thoughtless, and insuperably innocent, for being such a perfect representation of the people he serves… believes in good intentions and is astounded and offended when they’re not taken for the deed. He has never done anything for which to be hated and yet he is facing, daily and nightly, people who would gladly see him dead…” #quote 

Author claims there is a large distance between the police and civilians regardless of skin color. **Interesting story of the police officer at the party**. Had to leave despite the other person instigating the incident. “Once people know you’re a cop, you can’t have normal relations with them.”

This leads to **police solidarity** and a shrinkage of responsibility from everyday citizens. The public hands over to the police the dirty work of society they’d rather not acknowledge. Additionally police authority restricts individuals’ freedoms which naturally leads to resentment.

Police are trained to identify what’s normal and preserve it. They perpetuate the status quo and affirm. Makes them inherently conservative.

### Chapter 11

Prosecutor vs. police officer → Different socialization processes. Police officers see themselves as craftsmen or experts into crime and criminal investigation. They don’t see themselves as civil servants. Barriers and obstacles to the exercise of their discretion are _**bad**_ because it impedes their expertise. Also as a result of this type of thinking → efficiency is valued as the most important end goal.

Police not only have to deal with rule of law vs. maintenance of order (individual rights vs. coercion), but they must also deal with worker initiative vs. legal civil servant (innovate and use discretion vs. do not do those things).

One reform → **professionalization**. Achieve division of labor and administration along purely technical considerations. Emphasizes rationality and efficiency according to learned rules and expertise. Introduces fairness, calculability, and impersonality. **This is the wrong model** the author argues.

Bureaucracies succeed because they enable efficiency by allowing officials to exercise discretion intelligently. A belief in legality entails the rules being followed because they represent important guardrails (not barriers which must be learned on how to evade).

If professionalism is ever to work, it must involve more fundamental values amenable to the rule of law.

“The problem of police in a democratic society isn’t one of better technology or recruiting men with more years of education… what must occur is a significant alteration in the ideology of police so that police professionalization rests on values of democratic legal order rather than on technological proficiency.” #quote #highlight 

The purpose of the law is, in some sense, to make your job more difficult. **Legal professionalism** not **managerial professionalism**.

Must reward police for compliance with the law rather than for controlling crime. **Ultimate responsibility lies with its citizenry**. The police can hardly be expected to be much better than the political context in which it is operating.

An example → policing practice basically suggests a suspect is presumed guilty.

Police are also put in tough positions during crusades when actors in society push them or force them to abandon individual rights to catch the criminal _at all costs_.

“... advanced technology often results in greater violation. Technological advances… only make the police more competent to interfere with individual liberty.” #quote #highlight
